<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ871012-0045 </DOCNO><HL> Business Brief:Phoenix American Inc.</HL><DD> 10/12/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> PHXABUYBACKS, REDEMPTIONS, SWAP OFFERS (BBK) </IN><TEXT>   Phoenix American Inc., San Rafael, Calif., said it began a tender offer to buy back as many as 600,000, or 9%, of its common shares at $5 apiece.    Phoenix, which has about 6.4 million shares outstanding, said the plan &quot;confirms our pledge to focus our attention on internal growth.&quot; The offer expires Nov. 9 at 4 p.m. PST.    A spokeswoman for the financial services concern said the plan contains an option that allows the company to expand the buy-back to as many as 1.2 million shares, should any large blocks be tendered.    In national over-the-counter trading Friday, Phoenix closed at $4.75, up 37.5 cents.    The company organizes and manages limited partnerships that invest in high-technology equipment leasing and in cable television systems. In the fiscal year ended June 30, Phoenix had net income of $2.2 million, or 33 cents a share, and revenue of $23.9 million. </TEXT></DOC>